        <t:profileDesc xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">
            <t:creation/>
            <t:abstract>
                <t:p> A miniature showing the Crucifixion of  <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5684JesusCh">Jesus</t:persName>.
                    The scene may include a number of additional figures, such as the  <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS6819Mary">Virgin Mary</t:persName> or
                    <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5695John">John</t:persName>, the scene typically follows the account of the
                    <t:ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT1560Gospel">Gospels</t:ref>, but  may include iconographic elements inspired by
                    apocryphal sources.
                    
                    The three main typologies attested in the Ethiopian tradition are:
                    <t:list>
                        <t:item>Type 1 <t:desc>There is an Empty Cross and there are figures associated with it 
                            (i.e. it is not just an interlaced cross).</t:desc>
                  </t:item>
                        <t:item>Type 2 <t:desc>The body of  Living Jesus is nailed to the cross.</t:desc>
                  </t:item>
                        <t:item>Type 3 <t:desc>The body of the Dead Jesus is nailed to the cross.</t:desc>
                  </t:item>
                    </t:list>
                </t:p>
            </t:abstract>
